            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the cat dosage calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator uses your cat’s weight and a reference dose
                range (for example, 5–10&nbsp;mg/kg) to estimate how much
                medication might be given per dose. If you enter the strength of
                the product you have (such as 50&nbsp;mg tablets or 5&nbsp;mg/mL
                liquid), it also estimates the number of tablets or milliliters.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Core formula</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Total dose (per administration)</strong> = Weight (kg)
                  × Dose (mg/kg or units/kg)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-1">
                  <strong>Volume or tablets</strong> = Total dose ÷ Product
                  strength (mg per tablet, mg per mL, or units per mL).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step-by-step example</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>Cat weight = 4.0&nbsp;kg</li>
                <li>
                  Chosen drug: amoxicillin, 10–20&nbsp;mg/kg PO every
                  12&nbsp;hours
                </li>
                <li>Product strength: 50&nbsp;mg tablet</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                Minimum dose = 4.0&nbsp;kg × 10&nbsp;mg/kg = 40&nbsp;mg<br />
                Maximum dose = 4.0&nbsp;kg × 20&nbsp;mg/kg = 80&nbsp;mg
              </p>
              <p>With 50&nbsp;mg tablets:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Minimum: 40&nbsp;mg ÷ 50&nbsp;mg/tablet ≈ 0.8 tablet</li>
                <li>Maximum: 80&nbsp;mg ÷ 50&nbsp;mg/tablet = 1.6 tablets</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In practice, your veterinarian might round this to ½ or 1
                tablet, or choose a different strength or liquid formulation to
                make dosing easier and safer.
              </p>

              <h2>Important safety notes for cat medications</h2>
              <p>
                Cats are particularly sensitive to many drugs. Some medications
                that are safe for dogs or humans can be
                <strong>fatal</strong> to cats even at small doses. Always keep
                these principles in mind:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Never give human painkillers</strong> (such as
                  ibuprofen, naproxen, or acetaminophen) unless a vet has
                  explicitly prescribed them.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check organ function</strong> (kidney, liver, heart)
                  before using many chronic medications.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Adjust doses in seniors, kittens, and underweight
                    cats</strong
                  >
                  under veterinary guidance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Watch for drug interactions</strong> if your cat is on
                  multiple medications.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>When to call your veterinarian immediately</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You suspect your cat received the wrong dose or the wrong
                  medication.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your cat vomits repeatedly after medication or seems very
                  lethargic or unsteady.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You see swelling of the face, hives, difficulty breathing, or
                  collapse.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your diabetic cat’s appetite or water intake changes suddenly,
                  or they seem weak or wobbly.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations of online cat dosage tools</h2>
              <p>
                Even with accurate math, dosing cats is more complex than a
                simple mg/kg calculation. Veterinarians also consider:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Exact diagnosis and severity of disease</li>
                <li>
                  Lab results (kidney values, liver enzymes, blood sugar, blood
                  pressure)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Concurrent conditions (heart disease, hyperthyroidism, etc.)
                </li>
                <li>Other medications and potential interactions</li>
                <li>
                  How well the cat tolerates oral medications or injections
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For these reasons, treat this calculator as an
                <strong>educational guide</strong> to understand how
                weight-based dosing works, not as a prescription generator.
              </p>

              <h2 id="faq">Cat dosage calculator – FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is this tool suitable for insulin dosing?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator includes an example range for insulin glargine
                (in units/kg), but insulin therapy for diabetic cats must be
                individualized and closely monitored. Your veterinarian will
                usually start with a conservative fixed dose (for example,
                1&nbsp;U twice daily) and adjust based on blood glucose curves
                and clinical signs.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for over-the-counter medications?</h3>
              <p>
                Some OTC products (such as certain antihistamines or GI
                protectants) are sometimes used in cats, but the
                <strong>safe dose and formulation vary</strong>. Many human OTC
                products contain combination ingredients that are unsafe for
                cats. Always ask your vet before using any OTC medication.
              </p>

              <h3>How should I measure liquid medications?</h3>
              <p>
                Use the oral syringe or dropper provided by your veterinarian or
                pharmacy. Household teaspoons and droppers are not accurate. If
                the calculated volume is difficult to measure (for example,
                0.13&nbsp;mL), your vet may adjust the concentration or dose to
                something more practical.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Why does the calculator show a range instead of a single number?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Most veterinary formularies list dose <em>ranges</em> (for
                example, 5–10&nbsp;mg/kg) to allow flexibility based on the
                condition being treated, severity, and the individual cat. Your
                veterinarian decides where within that range your cat should be
                dosed.
              </p>

              <h2>Responsible use</h2>
              <p>
                Use this cat dosage calculator to better understand your vet’s
                prescriptions, to double-check that a dose is in a plausible
                range, or to compare different strengths and formulations. Do
                <strong>not</strong> use it to self-prescribe medications or
                change your cat’s treatment plan without veterinary approval.
              </p>
